'''Agnata Frances Butler''' (née '''Ramsay'''; 1867–1931) was a British classical scholar. She was among the first generation of women to take the [[Classical Tripos]] examinations at the [[University of Cambridge]], and was the only person to be placed in the top division of the [[British undergraduate degree classification|first class]] at the end of her third year, in 1887.  She married the [[List of Masters of Trinity College, Cambridge|Master of Trinity College]], [[Montagu Butler]], in August 1888, becoming the leading hostess in Cambridge.  She published a version of Book VII of Herodotus' ''[[Histories (Herodotus)#Book VII (Polymnia)|Histories]]'' in 1891.

==Early life and education==
[[File:Honour to Agnata Frances Ramsay.png|thumb|right|upright|260px|''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]'' published a cartoon by [[George du Maurier]] about her examination success.{{sfn|Kamm|2012|p=96}}  As she was the only person in the first class of the [[Classical Tripos]] that year, placing above all the men, [[Mr Punch]] and his dog Toby are shown ushering her into a [[first class travel|first class]] [[compartment coach|compartment]] which is for [[ladies-only car|ladies only]].{{sfn|Dash|2011}}]]
She was born Agnata Ramsay in London on 28 January 1867, the daughter of Sir James Henry Ramsay, 10th [[Ramsay baronets|Baronet of Bamff]], and Elizabeth Mary Charlotte née Scott-Kerr.  She came from a family with a history of academic achievement as her father published books on history,{{sfn|Lodge|Chibnall|2004}} her uncle [[George Gilbert Ramsay]] was a professor of humanity at Glasgow University and her grandfather, Sir George Ramsay, published works on philosophy.{{sfn|Budge|2004}}

Brought up in [[Perthshire]], she attended [[St Leonards School]] in [[St Andrews]].{{sfn|Delamont|2004}}  In 1884, she went as the Misses Metcalfes' Scholar{{sfn|Stephen|1933|p=173}} to [[Girton College, Cambridge]], where she read [[Classics]].{{sfn|Delamont|2004}}  Her achievement in being the only candidate in 1887 to be placed in the top division of the first class in the Classical Tripos examinations{{sfn|Beard|2017}} – thereby being placed above all of the men in her year – was marked with a cartoon in [[Punch (magazine)|''Punch'']] which was entitled 'Honour to Agnata Frances Ramsay' and showed her boarding a train's first-class compartment marked 'For Ladies Only'.{{sfn|Dash|2011}}{{sfn|Muller|2014}}

==Personal life==
[[File:A Pardonable Mistake.png|thumb|right|260px|The second [[George du Maurier|du Maurier]] cartoon in ''Punch'' about the 'crib for [[Herodotus]]']]
While a student, she worked hard at her studies but also found time for outdoor pursuits which she enjoyed, including tennis and skating.{{sfn|Stephen|1933|p=173}}  She was president of the debating society and, while she did not speak often, she impressed others with her eloquence and humility.{{sfn|Stephen|1933|p=173}}

In August 1888, she married the [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Trinity College, Cambridge|Trinity]], [[Montagu Butler|Henry Montagu Butler]].  They had met at the [[Cambridge Greek Play]],{{sfn|Beard|2017}} a performance of ''[[Oedipus Rex]]'' in November 1887 for which Butler had arranged a large party of 42.{{sfn|Delamont|2012|p=183}}  He had included Agnata because of her prowess in the classics but he later wrote that it was her "goodness ... not her Greek and Latin, which have stolen my heart".{{sfn|Delamont|2012|p=183}}  Even so, he allowed that, on their honeymoon, they "read a great deal of Greek together".{{sfn|Delamont|2012|p=183}}

They had three sons, [[James Ramsay Montagu Butler|James]], Gordon, and [[Nevile Butler|Nevile]].{{sfn|Delamont|2004}} Their first child was born while she was working on her edition of [[Herodotus]], which prompted ''Punch'' to run another [[pun]]ning cartoon, in which she was portrayed as ordering 'a crib for Herodotus'.{{sfn|Delamont|1989|p=145}}  James became an academic, and was [[Regius Professor of History (Cambridge)|Regius Professor of Modern History]] at Cambridge University; Gordon was killed in action in Egypt in 1916; Nevile became a diplomat, serving as British Ambassador to Brazil and to the Netherlands.

After the death of her husband in 1918, she remained in Cambridge, where she was involved in the local [[Christian Science]] church.{{sfn|Gartrell-Mills|1991|p=116}} She died in [[Harrow, London|Harrow]] on 27 May 1931.{{sfn|Delamont|2004}}

==Classical scholarship==
At Cambridge, she worked on a version of Book VII (''[[Polyhymnia|Polymnia]]'') of Herodotus' ''[[Histories (Herodotus)#Book VII (Polymnia)|Histories]]''.  It was published in the original [[Ancient Greek]] with notes in 1891, as part of [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]'s Classical series for colleges and schools.{{sfn|Butler|1891}}  She may have been the first British woman to produce an edition of a classical author.{{sfn|Lateiner|Gold|Perkins|2013|p=260}}  In 2006, [[Mary Beard (classicist)|Mary Beard]] wrote that "Agnata Ramsey was one of the most notorious casualties of the university marriage market", as she "did very little classics ever after".{{sfn|Beard|2006}}

Her husband, Montagu Butler, was friends with the [[poet laureate]], [[Alfred, Lord Tennyson]].  In 1892 the couple visited [[Farringford House]], where she and Tennyson discussed classical works such as the [[Alcaics]] of [[Horace]] and [[Sappho]]. She recalled his scepticism about the recent discovery of [[Troy]],{{sfn|Pearsall|2008|p=162}}{{quote|Then we spoke of [[Heinrich Schliemann|Schliemann]], of whom I had just been reading in [[Carl Schuchhardt|Schuchhardt]]'s book, and he said he had no faith in him.  'How could a great city have been built on a little ridge like that (meaning [[Hissarlik]])?  Where would have been the room for [[Priam]]'s fifty sons and fifty daughters?'}}

Another famous classicist was [[A. E. Housman]] who wrote in 1911 to thank her after a visit,{{sfn|Housman|2007|p=264}}{{quote|Dear Mrs Butler,<br><br>I have been solacing my journey home with your son's excellent verses which the Master was good enough to give me.  Oxford men, following [[Dryden]], sometimes refer to Cambridge as [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]].  Trinity Lodge, at any rate, seems to me a happy combination of Athens and [[Sybaris]].<br><br>I am yours sincerely<br>A. E. Housman}}

==Prize==
A prize for the best classics students in their second or third year was established and awarded by the Butlers – the ''Agnata Butler Prize''.{{sfn|Tuker|1907}}  Winners included [[Caroline Skeel]] (1893/4), [[Dorothy Tarrant]] (1907) and [[Barbara Wootton]] (1917).

