A '''timeline of the Holocaust''' is detailed in the events listed below. Also referred to as the Shoah (in Hebrew), [[the Holocaust]] was a [[genocide]] in which some six million European [[Jews]] were killed by [[Nazi Germany]] and its [[World War II]] collaborators. About 1.5 million of the victims were children. Two-thirds of the nine million Jews who had resided in [[Europe]] were murdered. The following timeline has been compiled from a variety of sources including the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]].<ref name="fcit">{{cite web |title=HOLOCAUST TIMELINE 1933-1945 |url=https://fcit.usf.edu/holocaust/TIMELINE/TEXTLINE.HTM |date=September 9, 2000 |author=College of Education, University of South Florida |location=Tampa, Florida}}</ref><ref name="history">{{cite web |author=The History Place |title=Holocaust Timeline |date=June 30, 2014 |work=A chronicle of the Nazi persecution of the Jews |url=http://www.historyplace.com/worldwar2/holocaust/timeline.html}}</ref><ref name="ushmm">{{cite web |title=The Holocaust and World War II: Timeline |author=Holocaust Encyclopedia |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |url=https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10007653 |year=2017}}</ref><ref name="gen">{{cite web |title=A Timeline of the Holocaust (1939-1945) |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/ForgottenCamps/General/TimeEng.html |date=April 2, 2002 |author=JewishGen.org |location=New York, NY}}</ref><ref name="tolerance">{{cite web |title=Timeline of the Holocaust |publisher=A Simon Wiesenthal Center Museum |author=Museum of Tolerance |location=Los Angeles, CA |date=February 2017 |url=http://www.museumoftolerance.com/site/c.tmL6KfNVLtH/b.5879251/k.72C8/Timeline_of_the_Holocaust.htm}}</ref>
==Timeline== {{expand list|date=February 2017}} {| class="wikitable" align="center" style="text-align:left;" width="98%" |- ! Date ! Major Events |- | align=right|24 February 1920 |In a speech before approximately 2,000 people in the [[Munich]] Festival of the [[Hofbräuhaus]], [[Adolf Hitler]] proclaimed the [[25-point program|25-Point Program]] of the [[German Workers' Party]], later renamed the [[Nazi Party|National Socialist (Nazi) German Workers' Party]]. Among other things, the program called for the establishment of a [[Pan-Germanism|Pan-German]] state, with citizenship, residency, and other civil rights reserved for ethnic Germans only, explicitly excluding Jews and all non-Germans. |- | align=right|18 July 1925 |[[Adolf Hitler]] publishes ''[[Mein Kampf]].'' |- | align=right|July 1932 |Nazis became the largest party in the [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]], capturing 230 of the 608 seats in the [[German federal election, July 1932|German federal election of July, 1932.]] |- | align=right | 30 January 1933 || [[Adolf Hitler]] appointed [[Chancellor of Germany]] |- | align=right | 27 February 1933 || The [[Reichstag fire]]. The subsequent [[Reichstag Fire Decree]] suspends the German Constitution and most civil liberties. |- | align=right | 9 March 1933 || [[Dachau concentration camp]] opens. |- | align=right | 23 March 1933 || [[Enabling Act of 1933]] enacted; lets Hitler [[rule by decree]]. |- | align=right | 1 April 1933 || [[Nazi boycott of Jewish businesses]] begins. |- | align=right | 7 April 1933 || [[Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service]], banning most Jews and Communists from government employment, is passed. Shortly after, a similar law affects lawyers, doctors, tax consultants, musicians, and notaries. |- | align=right | 29 April 1933 || [[Gestapo]] (German Secret Police) established |- | align=right | 10 May 1933 |[[Nazi book burnings]] begin. Books deemed "un-German," including all works by Jewish authors, are consumed in ceremonial bonfires. |- | align=right | July 1933 || The [[Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring]], calling for compulsory sterilization of the "inferior" |- | align=right | 21 September 1933 {{nobreak|– 23 December 1933}} || [[Leipzig trial]] acquits 3 of 4 men accused of Reichstag fire. Furious, Hitler establishes a [[People's Court (Germany)|People's Court]] to try political crimes. |- | align=right | 15 September 1935 || [[Nuremberg Laws]] are unanimously passed by the Reichstag. Jews are no longer citizens of Germany and cannot marry Germans. |- | align=right | 15 July 1937 || [[Buchenwald]] concentration camp opens |- | align=right | 12 March 1938 || Austria annexed by Nazi Germany (the ''[[Anschluss]]''). All German anti-Jewish laws now apply in Austria. |- | align=right | 29 May 1938 || Hungary, under [[Miklós Horthy]], passes the first of a series of anti-Jewish measures emulating Germany's Nuremberg Laws. |- | align=right | 14 July 1938 || [[Manifesto of Race]] published in [[Kingdom of Italy#Fascist regime .281922.E2.80.931943.29|Fascist Italy]], led to stripping the Jews of Italian citizenship and governmental and professional positions |- | align=right | 9–10 November 1938 || [[Kristallnacht]] |- | align=right | 13 May 1939 || [[MS St. Louis|MS ''St. Louis'']] sails from Hamburg to Cuba with 937 refugees, mostly Jews. Only 29 are allowed in. The rest, refused by Cuba, the United States and Canada are returned to Europe. |- | align=right | 18 October 1939 || first shipment of Jews to [[Lublin Reservation]] |- | align=right | 1 September 1939 || [[German invasion of Poland]] starts [[World War II]] in Europe |- | align=right | May 1940 || [[Auschwitz]] I opens |- | align=right | 22 June 1941 || [[Operation Barbarossa]] Germany invades the [[Soviet Union]] |- | align=right | 3 September 1941 || First gassings at [[Auschwitz]] using [[Zyklon B]] |- | align=right | 29–30 September 1941 || [[Babi Yar]] massacre of 33,771 Jews |- | align=right | 20 January 1942 || [[Wannsee Conference]] plans "[[final solution]]" |- | align=right | 27 March 1942 || first of at least 75,721 French [[The Holocaust in France|Jews deported from France]], to Auschwitz |- | align=right | 6 July 1942 || [[Anne Frank]] and her family go into hiding |- | align=right | 22 July 1942 || first deportation from [[Warsaw Ghetto]] to [[Treblinka]] during ''[[Grossaktion Warsaw (1942)|Grossaktion Warsaw]]'' |- | align=right | 23 July 1942 {{nobreak|– 19 October 1943}} || [[Treblinka]] death camp operates, 700-900 thousand Jews murdered |- | align=right | 19 November 1942 || first [[The Holocaust in Norway|shipment of Jews from Norway]] |- | align=right | 19 April 1943 {{nobreak|– 16 May 1943}} || [[Warsaw Ghetto Uprising]] |- | align=right | 2 August 1943 || [[Treblinka revolt]] |- | align=right | 14 October 1943 || [[Sobibór]] revolt and escape |- | align=right | 19 March 1944 || German troops [[Operation Margarethe|occupy Hungary]] |- | align=right | early May 1944 || first [[The Holocaust in Hungary|transport of Hungarian Jews]], to Auschwitz, began |- | align=right | 23 June 1944 || [[Red Cross]] representatives see elaborately staged Nazi propaganda ruse at [[Theresienstadt]] designed to portray camps as benign |- | align=right | 20 July 1944 || [[20 July plot|Attempt to assassinate Hitler]] fails |- | align=right | 23 July 1944 || [[Majdanek]], first major death camp liberated, by the advancing Soviet [[Red Army]] |- | align=right | 1 August 1944 || [[Warsaw Uprising]] begins |- | align=right | 4 August 1944 || [[Anne Frank]] and her family arrested and eventually deported to Auschwitz |- | align=right | 7 October 1944 || Crematorium IV at [[Auschwitz]] destroyed in [[Sonderkommando]] uprising |- | align=right | 25 November 1944 || [[Heinrich Himmler]] orders the gas chambers of Auschwitz destroyed as incriminating evidence of genocide |- | align=right | 27 January 1945 || [[Auschwitz]] death camp liberated by the Soviets. Anniversary is observed as [[International Holocaust Remembrance Day]]. |- | align=right | {{circa}} February or March 1945 || [[Anne Frank]] and her sister Margot die in Bergen-Belsen |- | align=right | 11 April 1945 || [[Buchenwald]] death camp liberated by the Americans |- | align=right | 15 April 1945 || [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] death camp liberated by the British |- | align=right | 29 April 1945 || [[Dachau]] liberated by the Americans and [[Ravensbrück]] by the Soviets |- | align=right | 30 April 1945 || [[Adolf Hitler]] suicide |- | align=right | 5 May 1945 || [[Mauthausen]] liberated by the Americans |- | align=right | 8 May 1945 || [[Theresienstadt]] liberated by the Soviets |- | align=right | 8 May 1945 || [[VE day]] — Germany surrenders unconditionally |- | align=right | 23 May 1945 || [[Heinrich Himmler]] suicide |- | align=right | 20 November 1945 {{nobreak|– 1 October 1946}} || first [[Nuremberg trials]], of 24 top Nazi officials |- | align=right | 2 July 1946 || Orson Welles' ''[[The Stranger (1946 film)|The Stranger]]'', first feature film with concentration camp footage, released. Hundreds more [[List of Holocaust films|feature films and documentaries about the Holocaust]] would be made. |- | align=right | 25 June 1947 || ''[[The Diary of a Young Girl]]'', Anne Frank's diary, is published in the Netherlands <ref>[http://www.annefrank.org/en/Anne-Frank/Publication-of-the-diary/Anne-Franks-diary-is-published/ Anne Frank’s diary is published], Anne Frank House web site, accessed 4 April 2017</ref> |- | align=right | 11 July 1947 || [[SS Exodus|SS ''Exodus'']] departs France for the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]]. Her 4,515 passengers, mostly Holocaust survivors, are intercepted by the British Navy and shipped back to camps in Germany. |- | align=right | 14 May 1948 || [[State of Israel]] declares independence |- | align=right | 11 May 1960 || [[Adolf Eichmann]], one of the major organizers of the Holocaust, is captured in Argentina, and brought to Israel where he is tried, convicted. |- | align=right | 31 May 1962 || [[Adolf Eichmann]] executed |}
